The topic of abortions and women reproductive health came up in a conversation with my friend group. We were very split in what we thought. I decided instead of shutting down and invalidating the feelings and views of my friends to be open and listen to what they had to say.
I was frustrated at first that they had such strong opinions about this one topic. I felt at ease when I was open and curious about what they had to say.
I listened, I put my phone away and maintained eye contact. I asked questions and did not raise my voice.
I learned that not everything is black and white. I can't assume the reasoning behind someones views.
I would have start off open rather than deciding the be open mid way through the conversation.

In 2020 I had a very hard time mentally, financially, and socially in my life. I created a list of the big roles I wanted to accomplish this year. I wanted to get my license, I would be the first women in my family to be able to have her license and drive. In my culture women driving isn't common. I made many other goals with which most I accomplished.
I was a little overwhelmed at first because I thought I had to complete all these goals all at once. I was also excited to transform my self and my life.
Once I wrote down my goals, I broke them down into more manageable small goals. I also set time lengths with when I want each goal to be accomplished. I also told my family and friends about my goals so they could hold me accountable and support me.
I learned how to set realistic measurable goals. I learned how to better organize my time in order to achieve my goals. I have learned to honor my life outside of school and work.
I would have made a couple of the goals more realistic.

I volunteered at a farm within my community, helping the farmer with chores around the farm. First we cut and removed some weeds. Later, we set up a grape vine trellis.
The work wasn't easy, but the results clearly demonstrate our effort.  The grape vine trellis we built turned out great. It could likely support a few hundred pounds of grape vine with ease.
I used a pair of garden clippers to cut some large weeds, and I built a grape vine trellis, using various tools such as hammers and drills to aid in the process.
I learned the design of a Modified Munson grape trellis, and how it is used to farm grapes.
Everything went well. The grape vine trellis we built turned out great, and I wouldn't do anything different.

I created an email flyer for an announcement for the yearbook, compiling information into a pretty flyer that contained all the information in an easy-to-understand format. I also reached out to the Director of Communications, asking for her to announce the flyer I made that told the results of the cover contest's winners.
During this experience, I felt creative and thoughtful, and then once I was finished I felt proud of my work. I always get a little nervous having to reach out to people, so I felt a little anxious in the process of emailing the Director of Communications, but allowed my pride and happiness with my work to overshadow that, and allowing me to have an easy experience reaching out to the Director.
I used technology and resources to create a flyer and I used creativity to take bare-boned information and make it into nice and easy-to-understand blurbs that made it an announcement. I used critical thinking to adjust my format to fit the flyer shape I wanted, as well as to determine if my work was visually pleasing.
I learned how to make a flyer that is capable of being sent out to students and staff announcing the results of the yearbook cover contest, using a unique formatting size for it. I also furthered my understanding of how to use Canva.
Things went well, and in the future, because I am more familiar with the platform and what I want from an announcement flyer, I hope to be more efficient in my work.

I set up before my school's literature group, putting the tables in a circle and handing out rubrics, as well as making sure every student had their work prepared. I facilitated conversation by posing thoughtful questions about the reading, helped others share their own thoughts, and invited everyone to participate. I also looked over their short constructed responses to the reading and marked them up for grammar or content issues, leaving recommendations and compliments.
During the seminar, I was proud of the conversation that the students were having and was happy to see that their conversation was starting to include considering the author and plot, rather than just discussing what happened in the book. When looking over SCRs I felt productive, and overall I was proud. Their SCRs, across the board, have improved dramatically, and while I had some students who simply seem to not learn from any of their mistakes and I feel a little frustration, that emotion was overshadowed by continued pride h=at having students improve on their SCRs.
I took leadership in the seminar, leading my peers through meaningful conversation while also being self-aware enough to keep myself from dominating the conversation, allowing others to develop their own thoughts and share them with the group. I also was able to be critical and review people's SCRs for grammatical errors and critique their writing content, making notes to help them improve their writing and literature analytic skills.
I learned that progress isn't always linear. While I saw great improvement across the board amount the SCRs, today's seminar and a select few of the SCRs went back on previous improvements: some SCRs were out of MLA format despite my steps taken to inform the students of MLA format and the conversation had more lulls and moments of no conversation than last time. I have hope they will continue to grow though, and this one day does not mean they haven't made progress.
In the future, I will prepare more thought-provoking questions to have prepared in case people across the board are allowing for more lulls in conversation. Additionally, one of the teacher's at my school asked me to speak a little on what content from the book would be good to put in an assignment for an outside class that connects to our literature group by making the students form a connection between the students and the literature group book, and next time I will speak on that.

I looked through potential themes for the yearbook, marking down a list of themes I think would work well for this year's yearbook for future reference with the yearbook team and supervisor. I emailed my school's director of communications at the prompting of my supervisor, asking her to add the link to my website to a yearbook announcement she had made as well as another announcement for the upcoming ordering of the yearbooks. I prompted myself to create two flyers, as well as planning to create more in the future, that spread awareness for the average student's ability to submit their own photos to potentially be in the yearbook through the yearbook website that I designed in the past.
I was working at a fast pace, finding my grove in the work for yearbook tasks that need to be being completed, creating the feeling of working hard without overworking myself leaving me feeling proud and productive. I used my own critical thinking and creativeness to look through potential yearbook themes as well as applying it to the flyers that I made during A.W.O.L. and it made me feel artsy and creative as well as productive.
I used analysis and critical thinking as I shortened a list of potential yearbook themes from over 300 to a list of 11 as well as designing thoughtful, eye-catching and informative flyers for photo submissions to the yearbook. I used good communication skills through all three of my tasks, thinking about how to best communicate to my future self about what themes were my favorites, what I needed from the director of communications, as well as how best to easily communicate to students and staff how they could best submit photos through the website I previously created. I also used self-direction and problem solving after my agenda for the day was complete but I still had work time, as I saw an issue (the lack of use of my photo submission forms on the yearbook website) and found a solution to the problem through flyers to spread awareness.
I learned further how to use my resources to create flyers that are concise but informative. I furthered my skills of writing emails to others and asking them to communicate through their resources to my target audience. And, I also learned how to better fill my undirected time with productive and gratifying work that both myself and and my supervisor can find useful and interesting.
Things went well today, and I will continue to use critical thinking to look for gaps where work needs to be done for something that I am becoming increasingly passionate about.

I shared my classroom with the ceramics class and managed to continue teaching without letting that become a distraction. Despite multiple kids having hardships staying on task, having the ceramics teacher there did help with wrangling the kids in. I also continued teaching basic skills to prepare for our winter donations!
I definitely began to feel frustrated leading up to the ending time due to the lack of participation and effort but I will say that I saw some growth in students I wasn't expecting and that made the experience much more tolerable and enjoyable. I did have fun watching my kids try their hands at ceramics, and the fact they cleaned up after themselves made my day that much easier.
I gave the struggling kids an ultimatum: they can learn ceramics with Emmy and properly engage or they can do craft stuff with me in preparation for winter. I also made my kids step up more during clean up time which went very well. The last thing I spent my time doing outside of school was continuing to finish up my 3 hats and a sweater I'm working on.
I learned that I might need to broaden my class with a skill that takes less time to develop and learn to wrangle in the difficult kids. I also learned that talking one-on-one with them really helped to establish goals and deadlines personalized to their availability and project. I also learned in term of projects, I need to complete them before I start new ones.
I would definitely try introducing another activity that takes less skill but is still necessary so kids feel more open to trying them. I also would've met with the kids sooner about their individual goals and deadlines, although it's worked out just fine thus far. Furthermore, I want to keep my kids concise on deadlines which means setting a good example and finishing my own projects before beginning new ones.

My school has literature groups that we participate in every Wednesday, and I volunteered to be one of two leaders for my group. With the help of my co-leader, I facilitated conversation about the most recent chapter section of our assigned book. I prompted people to participate in the conversation, asked questions to further the depth of understanding of the most recent section, and then graded the short constructed responses of those in my group, marking them up for grammar, spelling, structure, MLA formatting, and analysis issues.
Throughout this experience, I felt determined and proud. I am determined, and am taking actions towards encouraging, deeper analysis of the book itself, as well as getting everyone to follow correct MLA format. I was also proud of how much better this round of short constructed responses and conversation flow and depth was than previous rounds, already knowing that the students will continue to grow throughout the year.
I planned and prepared for the literature group seminar by creating questions of my own that would prompt conversation and analysis while also helping to guide students away from issues that my co-leader and I have been noticing during seminar and within short constructed responses. I guided and facilitated conversation and analysis of our assigned book, with the prepared direction and purpose. I also marked up the short constructed responses of the students, marking grammar and spelling issues, MLA formatting issues, analysis development issues, as well as marking where each student did well and should continue to replicate the thoughtful developments they wrote.
I learned more about facilitating a guided conversation as well as leading thoughtful analysis of a topic without spoon-feeding students my own ideas, prompting them to develop their own. I also learned how rewarding seeing growth is in others as a direct result of my own guidance and patience, encouraging me to continue to gently guide others to where they need to be.
This seminar went well, however, next time I will prompt people to come up with their own analysis questions for the group that encourages understanding the meaning behind the book, rather than just asking about and discussing the events of the book.

Over the course of teaching my Crafts for Service class, I have run into multiple behavioral problems with certain students. While this is to be expected, my lack of being an adult makes establishing authority much more difficult. Thus, there were kids leaving the class early as well as consistently bringing up inappropriate topics.
I felt extremely frustrated as I felt I had done my absolute best to cater to all of the kids' needs and it wasn't seeming to work with all of them. My frustration turned to anger when one of the students decided to spontaneously leave without permission, threatening both his and my positions. This made me feel both angry and guilty.
I spoke with both the counselor and the high school AWOL administrator to come up with a plausible solution that wouldn't tarnish the student's grades or reputation, it would simply provide an ultimatum (contract) with the child's best interest in mind.
I learned a whole lot more patience as well as how to practically and quickly set your boundaries and authority. By using a contract and a stern stance, I was able to solve the problem without involving other adults and without causing more conflict.
I would've talked with the counselor and AWOL advisor much sooner and drafted up my expectations at probably the 2nd week into AWOL.

I participated in a HAT tournament for ultimate frisbee. They put names in a generator and create randomized team built of people with different experience levels. The reason I was annoyed is that it was harder to understand, but it helped me understand what it's like to have to use that. I was frustrated because we had someone who could have used a closed captions accommodation instead of a voice narration.

My school had a sunrise hike for peace day on Tuesday, and as part of the yearbook team, I took the initiative to get up early and go to take photos and document the hike so we can have photos later in the year.

On a more personal note, I learned just how beautiful a sunrise hike can be, and I'd want to do another in the future.

I guided a literature group seminar as a literature group leader. I helped to facilitate the open flow of constructive conversation among those in the literature group, prompting people to speak and helping to keep there from being too long of a lull in conversation.
I felt prepared, organized, and calm throughout the experience. I knew what to do going into the seminar, what needed to be discussed, what my job would be in facilitating conversation, and what the goal of the seminar was, helping me to feel collected and prepared. Because I felt prepared and I'm not uncomfortable in positions of leadership when I know what is expected of myself and others, I was able to feel calm throughout the experience, helping others who were possibly nervous about sharing at the seminar to feel more relaxed as well.
I prompted and facilitated focused conversation on our literature group book (The Orphan Collector). I also checked the other students' short constructed responses to the reading for grammar and structuring, making notes of places that need correcting or improvement without grading the responses themselves.
I learned how to better prompt people to speak in possibly unfamiliar situations. I also learned how to recognize and fill a lull in conversation through my own input and questioning without dominating the room and conversation.
I think things went well this time, and in the future, I will continue to be confident and relaxed when leading the seminar to help people be comfortable in the space and in the conversation. The last time I ran literature group, I accidentally cut people off before they were finished sharing the entirety of their idea or point, and this time was careful to not cut people off before they were finished.

As part of my AWOL this week, I helped elementary teachers set up new materials in their classroom. One of the materials that I put together was manipulative fractions. This involved taking old fractions off of the shelf and unpacking new ones. I had to clean the new ones and organize them onto shelves.
I had difficulty deciding how to organize the fractions because they were not all standard circular fractions. Some of the fractions were squares or triangular pieces that could be put into a square shape. I ended up asking a third grader to help me because he had done the work before, and I wanted to find a way to include students.
I was careful in unpacking the new materials because they are fragike and I wanted to be cautious with materials that are not mine. I thought back to my own time in elementary and how we were taught to always hold or carry objects with both hands. When I was carrying fractions back and forth, whether new or old, I was careful to carry them gently.
This experience gave me a perspective on things learned at a young age that can be applicable later in life as well. It has been a long time since I have thought to carry something with two hands in such a considerate way.
I donÃ¢â‚¬â„¢t know that I would do anything differently. I enjoyed being able to assist others and find ways to include students in my work as well.

I worked with a parent and their son to find a bicycle suitable for his needs. He was training for a triathlon and wanted to be able to keep up on the road segments. This year, and this semester, I have had a lot on my plate. I play competitive soccer for a club, I have a course-load of 5 AP classes, I have a part-time job, and I also try to maintain a good sleep schedule, and social life. However, as I'm sure you can imagine, this is extremely difficult and I am not able to do all of this most of the time. Recently I have made the decision to quit my part time job because I feel as though that is the best decision, and the thing that I would be most ok with leaving my life. My high school soccer season is starting up in a few weeks as well, and I just didn't see how doing everything would be possible, while still remaining healthy and happy.
This was a hard decision because it involved a lot of stress and thinking about it. I am always stressed and exhausted so I knew this was the best decision, it was just hard because it almost feels like I am giving up, or quitting on something because I can't take it, but there is only so much one person can do and take.
After months of being miserable I finally reevaluated my situation and the things in my life that could be negatively impacting it. I decided which option was best for me and how I would be able to have more time, be less stressed, and just be happier and healthier overall.
I learned that it is ok to admit that you need a break, or make changes in your life for the better. It doesn't mean you're weak or can't handle things, it just means you know your limits and can decide to do what is best for you.
I would have done this so much earlier because I am already feeling less stressed and happier, and I know that I could have done this so much easier and not had to have been so miserable for so long.

I saw video on a social media platform talking about how someone had learned the Star Wars Aurebesh language. It seemed like an interesting thing to learn, and I love Star Wars, so I decided to learn it.
I was really excited during my learning process. When practicing translating the language to English, I would laugh when I got something wrong, or wasn't able to recall what some symbols meant.
I practiced translating for a good 30 minutes, and over this time period I was able to remember most of the symbols required to form sentences. I then took the time to write out the entire alphabet, began creating my own names, words and phrases, while I also worked on translating from English to Aurebesh.
I learned that it can be really fun to learn a new language. Most of high school I loved learning another language, but at some point it felt like it was getting shoved down my throat, and I didn't like it anymore. But learning Aurebesh helped me to remember how to love a language that's not my own and how two appreciate something that's outside of my understanding.
I don't think I would do anything differently. This was such a fun activity that didn't require me to communicate with others or set goals; nothing. It was easy to learn and such a carefree experience.

I am witnessing a slow, but steady decline in my motivation to and efficacy of work once more-while the haste of the end of the semester/2nd quarter invigorated me temporarily, domestic stress and the onset of college acceptances and the associated paperwork threatens to set me back to similar conditions that created the crisis. My hobbies and social motivation have begun to suffer as well.
As aforesaid, created a rigorous schedule of work and breaks that will, with any hope, allow me to clear my backlog and get back "on track" with my schoolwork before my grades begin to noticeably decline. Notable qualities include similar start and end dates for pre-covid schooldays (8:00 to 6:00), as well as a meal schedule that more closely resembles that of a functioning human being.
The folly of attempting to rely on free-form self-discipline alone to see me through the school year. While such tactics may have worked in the early quarters of summer and fall, the late stages of quarantine isolation, the winter season, and unforeseen domestic stress clearly require defined structure and rigor to endure.
Should I need to endeavor into another year of online learning (or, honestly, even the return to college under optimal conditions), I will need to set defined boundaries for myself in the absence of established structure even if they do not seem immediately necessary as, clearly, unforeseen complications can arise.

I've recently met someone in need of some level of support, and have tried a bit to be supportive.

They obviously don't want help, a lot of people in bad places don't. They don't think they deserve help. By trying to help convince them that it would be worth it, I've begun the first step toward them getting a whole lot better.
A lot of casually hanging out over games and occasionally having serious talks. I'm trying to establish an environment of safety and trust online, so that they are more willing to work through their issues with me.
While I have a long way to go in the world of psych, I've realized that I as a person feel a need to help others in order to be complete myself, and that working in psychology is certainly going to be my best way I could help other people.
While I have exhibited some frustration, I don't think it was to enough of an amount that I'd have to regret it. They're sensitive, and I wished that I wasn't frustrated by that.

After a period of lapse over winter break, I have begun to recover my original workout schedule and habits that I had previous, hoping eventually to restore myself to such a degree that I can once again complete my entire planned routine from over the summer before class each morning.
As typical, I was rather hard on myself in the initial weeks, forcing myself to go without a healthy amount of sleep in an attempt to rectify my schedule, with little success. I eventually came to forgive myself, however, in light of the fact that we are undergoing unprecedented times with both quarantine and these winter months.
I have eventually begun to rectify my sleep schedule in increments realizing that if I overdo it I simply waste as much time as I "gain" languishing in my exhaustion. Furthermore, I too have been easing into my routine in stages to allow my stamina to recover with effort and time.
I am coming to accept what I have long been told, that the exactness of one's routine matters less than simply making an attempt at the routine at all. Especially in the these motivation-sapping times, I am learning the value of simply doing anything, rather than doing nothing out of despair of not doing "enough"
In the future I'd obviously like to prevent my sleep schedule from spiraling out of control as it did previous, though this should be easier living either with my mother or on my own in college.

I developed a program with objectives and goals, and with the support of a community organization, was able to recruit scholars and speakers to host community educations sessions every evening over the course of the week. As part of it, we took folks into a debrief/breakout room and I led conversations and reflections to help them make connections between and across sessions, and to internalize their ideas.
I was tense in wanting everything to go well and for folks to be engaged, for speakers to have good experiences, and then to the learners for facilitating the breakouts.
I planed and wrote script, tried to stay in contact with speakers and ensure continuity and comfort, and developed debrief outlines to support others' reflective processes.
I was able to practice my facilitation skills and trust that I could maintain conversations and moderate sessions like this.
I would build in more opportunities for conversation and introductions for the folks who are participating in breakout groups, and I'd like to have longer sessions with the speakers to ensure that those who visit sessions are able to learn more. I'd also like to manage planning ahead of time so that we aren't scrambling to meet all the needs at the last minute.

Once more a routine occurrence in the dearth of notable "experiences" in this quarantine, I have routinely practiced violin since my middle school years.
Violin was an interesting struggle for me-with the instrument so close to the ear, one hears a much different rendition of the music compared to the spectator. A similar dynamic can be observed with art, and overall this lead to a pondering nature of both things in relation to self-perception and self-worth.
I aim to practice every day for approximately 15 to 30 minutes, with a formal lesson every Sunday. Every few months I'd prepare a piece for recital.
Recently, my violin teacher came to me with the admission that he believes there is little else he can teach me, the violin not being his specialty. Because of this, he is recommending me to a colleague more experienced with the instrument. I am sad to part with him because of the rapport we have built over these years, but am gladdened by this mark of my progress.
Over the years, and most especially in this motivation-sapping quarantine, I have been remiss in actually practicing every day. I hope to improve this rate in the new year, and hopefully with the coming of more psychologically healthy conditions.

With finals coming up this week, I have gone through each of my classes and decided which ones I need to do the best on, in order to do good in the class. This has helped me focus my studying to ensure that I get all As once the semester is over.
This has helped me to be less stressed because most of my classes I know I won't have any problems in, so it allows me to spend more time on the classes that I know I need the most help in. Doing this has allowed me to manage my time better and feel a lot more prepared for the exams coming up.
I started by figuring out what each class's final would consist of, whether multiple choice, free response, essay, etc. Then, I looked at my grades in each class and what types of scores I would need to satisfy the grade I wanted. I then figured out which classes I was understanding well, and which ones I was struggling in in understanding the material. I took all of these into consideration and decided which classes I should prioritize in my studying, and which ones I didn't need to worry too much about.
I learned that this is a good way to study as it really gives me a lot of time to focus on the things I need to be focussing on. For example, I really understand what I'm learning in AP psychology right now, have a pretty high grade, and the test is all multiple choice. Because of this I am not going to spend that much time studying for that test. However, for my AP computer science test, I have been struggling a little bit in there, I have a lower A in that class, and the test has both multiple choice questions and free response. Because of this, I am definitely going to be spending quite a bit time studying for that exam.
The only thing that I would do differently is start doing this earlier, in past years of high school, because I think its a really effective way of studying and takes a lot of stress off of me.

Moved houses from Sienna to Greenfield during the second quarter finals.
While much of the preparation for the move was completed while at my father's house, we began living in the new home shortly before and during the process of moving. Among the time investment was the aforementioned packing, the establishment of a workspace in my room, and the resolution of technical issues with wireless connection, the last part being particularly hindering in an online learning environment.
I had planned my end of quarter work on a strict timetable that failed to account for the delays of the move, teaching me that I must learn to plan ahead for such possible delays in the future.
As aforementioned, I would do better to more thoroughly check my future schedule for delays, and, in general, not put off work to such a degree that I end up with such a narrow deadline.

In order to completely understand my quiz mistakes, I went in for help during my teacher's office hours.
After going to office hours, I think I understand the material a lot better, and I do feel a lot better about the content itself because I now have a different way to look at how to deal with the problems.
I showed him which questions I had trouble with, what specifically I didn't understand, and then we worked through the problems together.
I learned that it's important to make sure you know exactly what a calculus question is asking for because even if you mess something up, it may still look like the right answer. I also learned that you should make sure to as clarifying questions so you can feel more confident about the content itself.
Next time, I'll apply everything I learned from these office hours into the other quizzes I'll take. I'll make sure to use any and all knowledge at my disposal and thoroughly check through my work.

Over the past few months I have been trying to go to bed earlier because if I don't, I wake up feeling really tired and with a headache. Going to bed earlier has helped me feel better during the day and allow me to get more schoolwork done so that I am less stressed.
This has been going really good, and I have definitely been able to get more sleep, and even be able to wake up earlier with no problem, which is something I struggled with before I started to do this.
I started by waking up a little bit earlier each day so that by nighttime, I would be more tired than normal, which allowed me to fall asleep earlier. I tried to keep a constant pattern of going to bed at relatively the same time each night, and waking up at the same time to allow my sleep patterns to adjust to this which would allow me to wake up easier.
I learned that having a regular sleep pattern and getting a lot of sleep is very important and beneficial. My schoolwork and performance has improved, and my overall happiness and quality of life has increased as well. My dad always told me to do this, and I haven't up until now, but now I understand why it's such a good idea for your health and ability to get things done.
The only thing I would do differently would be to start doing this earlier. Before covid happened, when we were going to school in person and coming home to do homework on top of sports, it was a lot easier to do this because we all had a constant schedule of going to bed and waking up for school, especially after being tired from a long day. However, once covid started, and all of our schedules became a lot more flexible, this became extremely hard. Doing this has helped things feel a little more normal and has added come consistency in my life. I wish I had started this last March, or continued my school schedule in March because it really has been very beneficial for me and my life.

This is less a single event and more a routine occurrence-I make a point of exercising ever weekday morning immediately after I wake up. I find that this allows me to avoid the lethargy of late evening and the inevitable procrastination in favor of schoolwork that my previously scheduled time suffered.
Over the summer, my routine consisted of about an hour of exercise through a kind of interactive exercise video program, though with the coming of the school year I've found I've had to shorten this to around 45-30 minutes.
The routine itself is a fairly even split between cardiovascular and targeted muscle exercise-the first half hour consisting of several intense, aerobic exercises such as leg scissors and knee lifts, and the last of more specific motions such as squats and planks.
This is more so a product of learning than a learning experience itself-this most recent routine is the sum of several past iterations of explorations into exercise, from little league soccer, to tai kwon do, to cross country. Of all these, chiefly I learned self-discipline, or the ability to force oneself into unpleasant action in the name of health or fitness.
As it stands, my regularity is suffering due, in turn, to my failing sleep schedule under online learning. Hopefully, with the "reset" of Winter Break, I will be able to rectify this unfortunate drift and restore consistency.

Had an enlightening conversation between friends regarding views on everything from religion, to transgender identities, to capitalism's ill effects on industry.
Mixed. I was delighted to find that my friends, who I took for average, unaware "gamers" and harmless, if ignorant, high schoolers had a great deal of tolerance for transgender identities, though the conversation hit a rough spot with regard to transgender athletes, where two notable stances were "the one time [he] could see transphobia being warranted" (is it ever?) to "I mean, it's rough but like..." (i.e indifference). To their point, it's a difficult situation, but I will admit their "solutions" aggravated me.
Argued on behalf of transgender athletes, pointing out that restrictions based on testosterone levels harm cisgender athletes in equal measure (e.g the case of Caster Semenya), but the consensus ultimately arrived at boiled down to the frustratingly resigned position that, since the affected persons remained few in number, there was little point in accommodation. Also attempted to guide a friend-himself a stringent atheist-through adjusting his condescending diction towards religious practitioners, though his social anxiety prevented the conversation reaching a point I was satisfied with.
Discourse, while unpleasant, is necessary to better consider and improve one's own views-for instance, while I still believe that transgender athletes are unfairly treated, the conversation yielded some "food for thought." I've also been given a new dilemma to consider-how to help a person who struggles with "filter". The aforementioned atheist has demonstrated on repeated occasions a propensity for immediately, and often rudely, speaking his mind-to his later shameful regret and self-flagellation. His tendency to immediately and nonverbally "shut down" during these moments of self loathing, and the frequency at which they occur, make guidance difficult, and, as of now, pending.
Had I not been preoccupied in the occasion, I would have liked to better research the matter of transgender athleticism, as it is a subject in which I'm relatively unacquainted. I also would have liked to have been previously aware of the full scope of the atheist's self loathing, as I could have then been immediately gentler.

A few weeks ago, I was playing my second to last game of soccer I would ever play in my club career. Me and another girl from the opposing team went up for the ball and we both fell. She landed on my leg and I was unable to walk on it. I had to go to the ER that day and they did x-rays. I couldn't finish the game, and our last game of the season was the next day, which I couldn't play either. Playing since I was 4 years old, it was really hard not to be able to play my last 2 games, but I knew I had no control over it.

I knew that I had no control over whether someone fell on me or not, and if my leg got hurt, but it was still painful to have to sit from the sideline watching my team play, without being able to go in.
Even though my leg was hurt and I couldn't play the next day, I still went to the game to watch in support. I knew that I didn't want to miss my last game, even if I wasn't playing. I tried to stay positive and just hope for a speedy recovery.
I learned that even the things you are most excited for can be taken away. It might not seem like a big deal, but it was to me. I learned that things that you can't control can control your life, and you just have to understand that there's not much you can do about it but try to stay positive and do what you can.
I would try not to get hurt next time, but that's something you can't really avoid, so I don't think there's much I could do differently. I still supported my team and tried to stay positive, which is good.

Today a non client called with great concern that her dog was experiencing a seizure, at the animal clinic I work in we are not taking on new clients as our hospital is at max capacity. I felt lots of empathy for this women and spoke with my doctor in regards to the situation, I was able to ask an existing client if he could move his non urgent appointment to a later time, the man was very understanding. With empathy, communication, and problem solving I was able to remediate the situation, and as a result the lady is now a huge fan of our clinic.
At first my reaction was to refer the anxious women on the phone to an Animal Emergency center, however I could hear the panic in her voice. This made me empathize with her and her dog and want to go the extra mile to help her.
1. I identified that while the issue was urgent, it was not dire and I knew our veterinarian could help
2. I gained approval from the doctor and offered alternative suggestions 
3. I negotiated with the existing client and convinced him to move his appointment
4. By handling the situation in a professional manner and empathizing we have secured a happy client and a healthy dog
I learned that even though the stress from every day work can make you detached to others' feelings, it is important to remain empathetic and put yourself in other peoples shoes whenever you can.
If I find myself in a similar situation in the future, I would identify schedule options before I presented the problem to my manager/doctor.

With everything around me being so overwhelming and full of uncertainty, online school has been something I have been able to organize, and figure out for myself. It keeps me busy while still being productive, and, most of all, brings constancy into my life. Like I said, I knew in-person school would bring more uncertainty and inconsistency into my life, with everything around me constantly changing, but online school has been something static, something that I have been able to change and evolve around, while it still remains the same and solid.
This was actually a really hard decision to make. At first, I was so sure I would be doing in-person school, I barely even gave any thought to it. Then, some time passed and it the thought of online school kept coming into my head, it was like I was subconsciously trying to tell myself to do it. I thought about it a little longer, and the more I did, I realized that this was going to be the rock in my life that I needed. While there were downsides, like not being able to see my friends at school, and never being able to go back to my home school, and basically missing out on my senior year, I decided to take the risk and try it out. Obviously it has worked out, but at the time I wasn't sure of that, and, keeping an open mind, it paid off.
I learned that not every decision in life should be made immediately. That taking the time to think through something is important to figure out what is best for you. I learned that even something you never would think of doing could be a good thing. Like I said, I never ever would have done online school if it wasn't for covid, but it turns out I really like it! I learned that keeping an open mind to things can allow you to discover things that you actually love. I really enjoy online school, and I never would have discovered that if I didn't give it a chance with an open-mind.
While I loved in person school when things were normal, who knows, maybe I would have loved online school back then as much as I do now. I would be more open to other education options, like online school, instead of just doing normal school. I never even thought of online school as an option, but now I would definitely make sure that I kept that as an idea.

Currently negotiating a difficult family situation as my mother recently had no choice but to move out after finding out that her then-fiance had dealt-and is dealing-with lifelong substance abuse, with no present plans to affect permanent change. While my own part consisted mainly of repeatedly assuring her I was of sound mental health in the face of her worries about this "uprooting", I was also a person she could "vent" to, as she hesitated to tell my father or sister until a resolution was met.
For my own part, I was less affected. I did not have a strong emotional attachment to this man nor the house from which we were moving, as I had only known both for a couple years. However I did worry for my mother-her strong emotional reaction to this was primarily owing to her own upbringing among parents who coped with addiction, and her tendency to forcibly put other's needs before her own as a coping mechanism under stress. The aforementioned discussions-in which I assured her the needs of myself and my sister were met and that she should concern herself with her own-were the means by which I expressed, and dealt with, my own concern.
Primarily, the aforementioned discussions were my actions, though I also offered my presence when she ultimately decided to break the news to my sister and father, though my mother declined.
Sometimes there is little you can do to physically help a person with their problems (i.e "solve" them), but a lent ear and even simply the offer of support can be succor enough.
Perhaps involve myself more in my mother's household should she choose to begin dating again. If I had been more engaged with this previous partner, perhaps I could've detected this issue earlier (or, at least, been of greater assistance when it occured)
